  <!--           <!-\- </p> -\-> -->
  <!--     </subsection> -->

  <p>
    To begin we will need the concept of an <term>open cover</term> a set. 
  </p>
  <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONOpenCover">
    <title>
      Open Cover
    </title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S</m> be any set in <m>\RR</m>, and let
        <me>I=\bigcup_{n=1}^\infty{}(a_n,b_n)</me> be the union of a
        collection of open intervals. Then <m>I</m> is called an
        <term>open cover</term> of <m>S</m> if and only if
        <me>
          x\in S \imp x\in I
          </me>.

          (Our definition specifies that the collection of open
          intervals be countably infinite, but a cover is allowed to
          be a finite collection as well.)
      </p>

    </statement>
  </definition>
<p>
  Loosely speaking, and <term>open cover</term> of a set <m>S</m> is a
  collection of open intervals which <q>cover</q> <m>S</m> (hence the
  name). Obviously every open interval is an open cover of itself. 
</p>
