      <p>
        <m>\left\{a\right\} </m> where <m>a\in \RR{}</m>.
      </p>
</statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5\right\} </m>.
      </p>
</statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <m>(0,1)</m>
      </p>
</statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <m>[0,1]</m>
      </p>
</statement>
  </task>
  <!--   <task> -->
  <!--     <statement> -->
  <!--       <p> -->
  <!--         <m>\NN{}</m> -->
  <!--       </p> -->
  <!-- </statement> -->
  <!-- <hint> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     The sets in your cover do not have to be the same size. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </hint> -->

  <!-- </task> -->

</problem>
<p>
  That we called <m>\lambda_o (S)</m>  and <em>outer</em> measure suggests that there is something called an <term>inner measure</term> and indeed there is. It<rsq/>is definition is given in <xref ref="DEFINITIONInnerMeasure" ></xref>.
</p>
<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONInnerMeasure">
  <title>
    Lebegue<rsq/>s Inner Measure
  </title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>S\subseteq [a,b] \subset \RR </m> be a set, and let <m>S^C</m> be its complement as in <xref ref="DEFINITIONOpenSet" ></xref>. The the <term>inner measure</term> of <m>S</m> is given by
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONInnerMeasure">
        \lambda_i(S) = [b-a]-\lambda_o([a,b]-S)
        </men>.
    </p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
  A couple of observations regarding this notation will be helpful here.
  <ul  marker="disc">
    <li>
      <p>
        Since <m>[b-a]</m> and <m>\lambda_o</m> both represent numbers
        the first subtraction in <xref ref="EQUATIONInnerMeasure"
        >equation</xref> is just ordinary subtraction.
      </p>
    </li>    
    <li>
      <p>
        The expression <m>[a,b]</m> normally means the interval from
        <m>a</m> to <m>b</m> which means that the points in the
        interval are ordered, but we are abusing our notation a bit by
        thinking of it simply as an unordered set. In that case the
        expression <m>[a,b] - S</m> represents set deletion rather
        than ordinary subtraction. It represents the set of points
        between <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> (inclusive) with the points in
        <m>S</m> deleted.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>

<p>
  The names of the inner and outer measures are descriptive. To
  compute <m>\lambda _o</m> we consider a set of numbers generated by
  a collection of sets which contain <m>S</m>. To compute
  <m>\lambda_i</m> we consider a set of numbers generated by a
  collection of sets which are contained within <m>S</m>. When these
  are the same we have the <term>Lebesgue Measure</term>.
</p>

  <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONLebesgueMeasure">
    <title>
      Lebesgue Measure
    </title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Given a set <m>S\subseteq [a,b]\subset \RR</m> if
        <m>\lambda_o(S)=\lambda_i(S)</m> then their common value is the
        <term>Lebesgue measure</term> of <m>S</m>, denoted <m>\Lambda(S)</m>.

      </p>
    </statement>

  </definition>

  <p>
    Because the <term>Lebesgue Measure</term> depends on the notion of an infimum, the possibility of an non<ndash/>measureable set exists. 
    The first non<ndash/>measurable set was described
    by 
    <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Vitali/" >
      Giuseppe Vitali</url> (1875-1932) in <m>1905</m>.  Creating such
      a set requires the use of something called the <term>Axiom of
      Choice</term> and delves deeply into a careful study of the
      theory of sets.  We will see how complicated sets can be in the
      next section.

  </p>
  <figure  xml:id="FIGUREGiuseppeVitali">
    <caption>    Giuseppe Vitali</caption>

    <idx><h>Portraits</h><h>Vitali</h></idx>
    <idx><h>Vitali, Giuseppe</h><h>portrait of</h> </idx>

    <image source="images/Vitali.png" width="35%">
      <shortdescription>Portrait of Giuseppe Vitali</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p> 
    For the remainder of this section we will only be discussing and
    using the <xref ref="DEFINITIONOuterMeasure" text="custom">Outer
    Measure</xref>. This will be enough to give you a good intuitive
    feel for the <term>Lebesgue Integral</term> which we define below.
    We have included the definitions of <xref
    ref="DEFINITIONInnerMeasure" text="custom">Inner Measure</xref>
    and <xref ref="DEFINITIONLebesgueMeasure" text="custom">Lebesgue
    Measure</xref> for completeness.
  </p>



  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Notice that <term>outer measure</term> is by definition an -->
  <!--   infimum. Since not all infima exist, there is the possibility that -->
  <!--   some sets might be <term>non<ndash/>measurable</term>. -->
  <!-- </p> -->




  <p>
    You saw in parts (a) and (b) of <xref ref="PROBLEMOuterMeasure1"
    ></xref> that finite sets have outer measure equal to zero.  So do
    some infinite sets.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMMeasureZero">

    <idx><h>measure zero</h></idx>
    <idx><h>zero measure</h><see>measure zero</see></idx>
    
    <statement>

      <p>
        Let <m>S=\{s_1, s_2, s_3, \dots \}</m> be countably
        infinite set of real numbers.  Let <m>\eps \gt 0</m> be
        given.  There is a collection of open intervals <m>(a_n,\
        b_n)</m> with <me>S\subset \bigcup^{\infty
        }_{n=1}{\left(a_n,\ b_n\right)}</me> and <me>\sum^{\infty
        }_{n=1}{\left(b_n-a_n\right)}=\eps </me>

      </p>
      <p>
        Such a set is said to have <term>measure zero</term>.
      </p>


    </statement>
  </theorem>

