<paragraphs>
  <title>
    The Lesbegue Integral
  </title>



  <p>
    A primary objective of this text is to convey to you, the student,
    an appreciation for, and an understanding of, the need for
    rigor. That objective remains in force. However, in this section
    we are at the edge of very deep mathematical waters. Until we
    start the next section we will only be wading in the shallows.  We
    will thus relax our relentless emphasis on rigor for now.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the rest of this section we will set rigor to the side and
    instead appeal to your intuition by the use of sketches. We will
    also reason by analogy rather than precisely (e.g., using <m>\eps
    </m>) and <m>\delta{}</m>. 
  </p>
  <p>
    In addition, for the remainder of this section we will assume that
    all of the functions we will consider are positive so that we can
    safely engage your strong intuitive understanding of area. We do
    this because our goal here is only to give you a sense of how
    Lesbegue broadened Cauchy<rsq/>s definition of the integral. In
    particular we will not develop Lebesgue<rsq/>s integral in
    detail. Should you desire a deeper understanding than you<rsq/>ll
    get here a second course in Real Analysis is highly recommended.
  </p>


  <p>
    <idx><h>Dirichlet Function</h></idx>

    Recall from <xref ref="PROBLEMDiricheletCountrExamp" ></xref>
    that the <term>Dirichlet Function</term>
    <me> 
      D(x)=
      \begin{cases}
      0, \amp \text{ if }  x \text{ is rational}\\
      1, \amp \text{ if }  x \text{ is irrational}
      \end{cases}
    </me>
    is not Riemann (Cauchy, Darboux) integrable. Dirichlet invented
    his function as an example of a non<ndash/>integrable
    function. For our purposes it has no importance beyond
    that. However the existence of non<ndash/>(Riemann)integrable
    functions suggests the question: Can the integral be defined in
    such a way as to capture all of the intuitive features of
    (Riemann) integration known to <m>18</m>th century mathematicians
    and which also allows us to integrate something as seemingly
    bizarre as the Dirichlet Function?
  </p>
  <p>
    The answer, of course, is yes. Otherwise we wouldn<rsq/>t have
    asked. Lebesgue defined such an integral at he turn of the twentieth century.
  </p>
  <p>
    Speaking <em>very</em> loosely, if we want to compute
    <m>\int_a^bf(x)\dx{x} </m> where <m>f(x)\ge 0</m> using the
    Riemann (Cauchy) integral we partition the <m>x-</m>axis into
    adjacent intervals with width <m>\dx{x}</m> and then construct
    (infinitesimal) rectangles with area 

    <me>
      f(x)\dx{x} 
    </me> 
    from each differential. Summing these areas <mdash/> computing
    <m> \int_a^b f(x)\dx{x} </m> <mdash/> provides the value
    of the definite integral.
  </p> 

  <p>
    <!--   To compute the area of the rectangle -->
    <!-- constructed at <m>x</m> we need its height, <m>f(x)</m>, and its -->
    <!-- width, <m>\dx{x}</m>.   -->
    <!-- </p> -->

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Rather -->
    <!--   than summing the areas of the rectangle one at a time proceeding -->
    <!--   from <m>a</m> to <m>b</m>  -->
    <!--   came up with a different approach -->


    Lebesgue<rsq/>s idea was to find all rectangles with a common
    height first, gather them together, and sum those areas. In letter
    to a colleague he described his process as follows:
  </p>
  <blockquote>

    <p>
      <q>I have to pay a certain sum, which I have collected
      in my pocket. I take the bills and coins out of my
      pocket and give them to the creditor in the order I
      find them until I have reached the total sum. This is
      the Riemann integral. But I can proceed
      differently. After I have taken all the money out of
      my pocket I order the bills and coins according to
      identical values and then I pay the several heaps one
      after the other to the creditor. This is my integral.</q>
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <!-- <figure  xml:id="FIGURELebesgue"> -->
  <!--   <caption>Henri Lebesgue</caption> -->

  <!--   <idx><h>Portraits</h><h>Lebesgue</h></idx> -->
  <!--   <idx><h>Lebesgue, Henri</h><h>portrait of</h></idx> -->

  <!--   <image source="images/Lebesgue.png" width="35%"> -->
  <!--     <shortdescription>Portrait of Henri Lebesgue</shortdescription> -->
  <!--   </image> -->
  <!-- </figure> -->

  <p>
    To see how this worked suppose we want to integrate
    <m>f(x)=\abs{\sin x}</m> from <m>x=0</m> to <m>x=\pi{}</m> as seen in <xref ref="FIGURELebegInt1" ></xref> below.
  </p>


  <figure  xml:id="FIGURELebegInt1">
    <caption>In Lebesgue<rsq/>s integral we find the area of each
    colored region first. Notice that there are <m>29</m> regions,
    including the two very thin red regions and three regions with
    zero height located at <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=\pi{}</m>, and
    <m>x=2\pi{}</m>.  </caption>
    <image source="images/LebInt2.png" width="100%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

<p>
  In a Riemann integral we start at <m>x=0</m>, compute the first blue
  area, add to that the first green area, and so on, until we reach
  <m>x=2\pi </m> where we add in the last blue area. Notice that area of
  the first blue rectangle is the height of <m>f(x)</m> multiplied by
  the measure of interval on the <m>x-</m>axis which corresponds to
  the interval <m>\left[ \frac17, \frac27 \right]{}</m> on the
  <m>y-</m>axis. We<rsq/>ll designate that area with
  <m>\mu{(1)}</m>. Similarly <m>\mu (2)</m> represents the measure of
  the base of the first green rectangle, and so on for all <m>26</m>
  regions. (Don<rsq/>t forget the thin red regions. We<rsq/>ll get
  back to those in a bit.)
</p>
<p>
  But nothing says we must add the areas in this order. This is just a
  convention. Lebesgue<rsq/>s ideas was to compute the area of all of
  the blue regions together, then all of the green regions, then the
  orange, and so on. By rearranging the sum this way the total are of
  the blue regions is,

  <me>
    f(1/7)\mu (1) +f(1/7)\mu (13) +f(1/7)\mu (14) +f(1/7)\mu
    (28)
    </me>
    or 
<me>
  f(1/7)\underbrace{\left[ \mu (1) +\mu (13) +\mu (14)
  +\mu(28)\right]}_{=\Lambda_b} 
  </me>.

  The expression <m>\left( \mu (1) +\mu (13) +\mu (14)
  +\mu(28)\right)</m> then represents the total measure of the bases
  on the <m>x-</m>axis of the blue regions which we designate
  <m>\Lambda_b</m>. <m>\Lambda_b</m> is the Lebesgue measure of the
  base of all of the blue regions. Similarly the Lebesgue measure of
  the dark green, orange, light green, purple,  yellow, and red regions are
  <m>\Lambda_d</m>, <m>\Lambda_o</m>, <m>\Lambda_l</m>,
  <m>\Lambda_p</m>,  <m>\Lambda_y</m>, and <m>\Lambda_r</m> respectively.
</p>
<p>
  Our integral is thus 
  <md>
    <mrow>  
      \int_{x=0}^{2 \pi}f(x)\dx{x}=f(1/7)\Lambda_b + f(2/7)\Lambda_d \amp{}+
      f(3/7)\Lambda_o
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
      \amp{} + f(4/7)\Lambda_l + f(5/7)\Lambda_p + f(6/7)\Lambda_y 
    </mrow>
  </md>
</p>
<p>
  But wait a minute! What about the two thin red regions and the ones
  at <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=\pi{}</m>, and <m>x=2 \pi{}</m>? Why did we leave them out?
</p>
<p>
  It should be clear that the measure of these regions must be
  zero. Do you see why?  The only places on our graph where <m>f(x) =
  1</m> are at the two maxima, and the base of any rectangle
  constructed there will have measure zero, <m>\Lambda_r = 0</m>. This
  is clear from the sketch. Moreover in light of part (a) of <xref
  ref="PROBLEMOuterMeasure1" ></xref>. A single point on the
  <m>x-</m>axis has measure zero.

  Thus
  the <q>area</q> of those regions will be <m>1\cdot \Lambda_0 =
  1\cdot 0 = 0</m>. Those points in the domain of our function
  contribute nothing to the integral.
</p>
<p>
  The same is true of the rectangles constructed at <m>x=0</m>,
  <m>x=\pi{}</m>, and <m>x=2\pi{}</m>. (Their heights will also be zero but that is irrelevant.)
</p>





