<p>
  In Lebesgue<rsq/>s scheme there is always the possibility that after
  rearranging our rectangles the measure of the base of a region might
  be zero.  <xref ref="FIGURELebegInt1" ></xref> shows two ways that
  can happen but there are many others. In particular, <xref
  ref="THEOREMMeasureZero" ></xref> shows that it is possible for an
  infinite set to have measure zero.  This has repurcussions for the
  integral of Dirichlet<rsq/>s function,

  <me> 
    D(x)=
    \begin{cases}
    0, \amp \text{ if }  x \text{ is rational}\\
    1, \amp \text{ if }  x \text{ is irrational}
    \end{cases}
    </me>, 

    which we will explore next. 
</p>
<p>
  For our later convenience we define the following
  notations. 
  <ul>
    <li>
      Let <m>\cal{I}</m> represent the set of irrational
      numbers in the interval <m>[0,1]</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Let <m>\cal{Q}</m> be the set of rational numbers in the same interval. 
    </li>
  </ul>   
</p>

<p>
  Since <m>D(x)</m> takes on only two values, <m>0</m> and <m>1</m>,
  we need only partition the <m>y-</m>axis in two places, <m>y=0</m>
  and <m>y=1</m>. Gathering all of the rectangles together in the same way we did  above  we see that
  <men xml:id="EQUATIONDirichFunc">
    \int_0^1D(x)\dx{x} = 0\cdot{} \Lambda \left( \cal{I}\right){}+ 1\cdot
    \Lambda\left( \cal{Q}\right) .
  </men>
</p>
